<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
	<!--
	  v0.29.4: re-sign entitlements for the bundled OpenCode helper
	  binary (Vendor/opencode/opencode) and the bundled `uv` binary
	  (Vendor/uv/uv). Both ship pre-built upstream and arrive ad-hoc
	  signed (TeamIdentifier=not set, flags=0x20002).

	  The XProtect dialog "Apple could not verify '.bbb…-00000000.dylib'
	  is free of malware" fires on macOS Tahoe whenever an unsigned
	  process dlopens a freshly-extracted Bun runtime module. The
	  Bun-compiled opencode binary writes those temp dylibs to TMPDIR
	  every time it boots, and the OS, seeing no trust chain on the
	  loader, pops the dialog mid-Codex-poll.

	  Fix: re-codesign these helpers under our Apple Development team
	  identity with the hardened runtime turned on and library
	  validation explicitly disabled. Once they carry our trust chain,
	  XProtect lets the dlopens through silently (Bun's extracted
	  modules are unsigned by design, hence the disable-library-validation
	  flag).

	  Why not also enable allow-jit / allow-unsigned-executable-memory?
	  Because Bun ships an AOT-compiled binary — the JS interpreter is
	  precompiled, no runtime JIT. allow-unsigned-executable-memory
	  would only matter if we shipped a JIT'd JS engine, which we
	  don't. Keep the surface minimal.
	-->
	<key>com.apple.security.cs.disable-library-validation</key>
	<true/>
</dict>
</plist>
